{"/service/ndnp/fu/batch_fu_edugator_ver01/data/sn88074815/00271765873/1914022001/0090.xml":{"full_text":"WHY WE SUCCEED\nThe success of any business depends solely on the\nmen who manage its affairs.\n#\\y\nThe Board of Directors of this bank is composed\nof men who have made a success of their own affairs,\nand are Directors who Direct.\nWe hare exceptional facilities for handling YOUR\nbusiness.\nThe Commercial Bank\nOCALA. FLORIDA\nCapital. $60,000.00 Surplus and Profits, $41,500.00\nDIRECTORS\nB. C. WEBB. Kendrick J. P. PHILLIPS. Ocala.\nPres. Standard Lime Cos. vice Pres, and Gen. Mgr.,\nW. H. McRAINEY, Wildwood. Ocala Telephone Cos.\nMcRAINEY BRIDGES. j c BOOZER G cala.\nD. E. tIcIVER, Ocala. Retired Banker.\nJ. R. WILLIAMS Citra. D. C. STILES, Jr., Ocala.\nCapitalist. ashler\nE. A. OSBORNE, Morriston. GEORGE J. BLITCH. Ocala.\nLumber and Naval Stores. President.\nRESOLUTION\nAdopted by Board of Public Instruc\ntion of Marion County on Tuesday,\nFebruary 3. 1914, Relating to Issu\ning Bonds for Citra Special Tax\nSchool District.\nMr. J. 6. Grantham introduced the\nfollowing resolution, which was\nadopted:\nWhereas. On the third day of Feb\nruary. 1914, there was presented to i\nthis board a petition signed by not\nless than It per cent, of the duly\nqualified electors, and of these not\nless than twenty-five per cent, of the i\nfreeholding electors of. and residing\nIn. Citra Special Tax School District\nNo. Ten. of Marion county. Florida, i\nwho are owners of freeholds in said\ndistrict, requesting this board to call\n\u2022n election pursuant to chapter 6542\nof the acta of the legislature of the I\nstate of Florida, approved May 16th,\n1913, to determine whether bonds in,\nthe amount of eight thousand\ndollars snail be issued bv said dis\ntrict. the proceeds of which are to be\nused for the purpose of building, en\nlarging and repairing school houses in\nsaid district and furnishing the same, j\nso and tor the payment of all indebted- j\nii*\u2018ss of said district existing at the\ntime of the Issuance of said bonds\nand Incurred for the exclusive use of j\nthe public free schools in said dis\ntrict. all of which will appear by the\nsaid petition on file In the office of\n\u2022aid board, and.\nWhereas. Cpon Investigation it ap\npears that said petition is signed by j\nnot leas than twenty-five per cent, of\nthe duly qualified electors of said dis-\nmU, and of these not less than twen-\ntv five per cent, of the free-holding\nglt-1 of said district, who are own\ners of freeholds therein, and that the\n\u2022sme Is In the form required by law\nnow, therefore, be it\nResolved. Hy the Board of Public\nInstruction for\" tht ocunty of Marlon,\nstate of Florida, that it is hereby de-\nItcrmined at this the first meeting of\n\u25a0\u2022aid board after the receipt of said\n\u25a0petition that eight thousand <ssoo\"\nidollars Is the amount of Imnds requir\nlad for the purpose set forth in said\n\u25a0petition, to-wlt Building, repairing\n\u25a0and enlarging school houses in the\n\u25a0said district, and furnishing the same.\n[Cud for the payfent of all indebted-\nEeas of said district existing at the\n\u25a0lime of the issuance of said bonds.\nEnd Incurred for the exclusive use of\nKhe public free schools in said dis-\nErte-t; that the rate of interest to be\nKp|d on said bonds shall be five per\nKent, per annum, due and payable\nKsml-ar.nuallv after bonds are issued\nEach year until said bonds are paid:\n\u25a0hat the principal of said bonds shall\nKe due and payable twenty years from\nBfe date of their issuance.\nUpon motion, it is ordered that the\nEtmgoing resolution be forthwith pub\nHished once each week for four con-\nKtcutive weeks In the Ocala Banner.\nKeewspaper published in the said\nBounty of Marion, state of Florida.\n\u25a0here being no newspaper published\nHn Citra Special Tax School District, i\nI Upon motion it is ordered that an\nElection shall be held on the lTth day\nBf March. 1914, In Citra Special Tax\nKtstrict No. Ten of Marion County. J\nEBlortda to determine whether or not i\nBhere ahall be issued by said district j\nEe bonds provided for in the forego-\nE, resolution. ami that notice of said\nElection be forthwith published once\nBtch week for four consecutive weeks\nBp the Ocala Banner, a Newspaper\nBublUhed in Marion County. Florida.\nBhere being no newspaper published\nCitra Special Tax School Dis-\nBrict Number Ten.\nJ. H. BRINSON, Secretary.\n**2o-41.\nElf Alabama wants competent and\nELthful service in congress she will\nB||ect Mr. Underwood for senator\nBays the Savannah News. He has\nRendered excellent service in the\nBpnae and in Jhe senate would wield\ngreat iufluence. Mr. Hobson would\nBo a great deal of talking there but\nKlan'i so much as deeds that the peo\n\u25a0\u25a0a want these days and Hobsou\u2019s\nBik of an alurmisi and jiugoist.\nNOTICE\nOf Application for Tax Deed Under\nSection 8 of Chapter 4SBB, Laws\nof Florida\nNotice is hereby given that Freder\nick W\\ Turner, purchaser of tax cer\ntificate No. 595, dated the 3rd day of\nOctober, A. D., 1898, has filed said cer\ntificate in my office, and has made\napplication for tax deed to, issue in\naccordance with law. Said certificate\nembraces the following described\nproperty situated in Marion county,\nFlorida, to-wit: Se!4 of nwVi, sec 20,\ntp 13, s, r 23, e. The said land being\nassessed at the date of the issuance\nof such certificate in the name of J.\nf\u2019ooper Mathers. Unless said certifi\ncate shall be redeemed according to\nlaw, tax deed will issue thereon the\n23rd day of March, A. D., 1914.\nWitness my official signature and\nseal this the 14th dav of February, A.\nn., 1914.\n(Seal.* P. H. NUGENT,\nClerk Circuit Court, Marion v_o., Fla.\n2-20\nNOTICE\nOf Application for Tax Deed Under\nSection S of Chapter 488S, Laws\nof Florida\nNotice is hereby given that William\nSnider, purchaser of tax certificate\nNo. 325, dated the sth day of June, A.\nD., 1911, has filed said certificate in\n!my office, and has made application\nfor tax deed to issue in accordance\ni with law. Said certificate embraces\nIthe following described property sit\nuated in Marion county, Florida, to\nwit: Lot 19, sub of ne*4 of ne*/ 4 sec\n13, tp 15, s. r 21 \u20145 acres. The said\nland being assessed at the date of the\nissuance of such certificate in the\nname of Mrs. L. A. Clute. Unless said\ncertificate shall be redeemed accord\ning to law, tax deed will issue thereon\nthe 23rd day of March, A. D., 1914.\nWitness my official signature and\nseal this the 14th day of February, A.\nD.. 1914.\n(Seal.) P. H. NUGENT,\ni Clerk Circuit Court, Marion Cos.. Fla.\n2-20\nNOTICE\nOf Application for Tax Deed Under\nSection S of Chapter 4888, Laws\nof Florida\nNotice is hereby given that W. H.\nWaddell, purchaser of tax certilcate\nNo. 746, dated the Ist day of June, A.\nD.. 1908, lias filed said certificate in\nmy office, and has made application\nfor tax deed to issue in accordance\nwith law. Said certificate embraces\nthe following described property sit\nuated in Marion county, Florida, to\nwit: Xw Vi of swVt of sec 34, tp 16, s.\nr 23. e. The said land being assessed\nat the date of the issuance of such\ncertificate in the name of A. A. Day\nton. Unless said certificate shall be\nredemed according to law. tax deed\nwill issue thereon on the 23rd day of\nMarch. A. D., 1914.\nWitness my official signature and\nseal this the 17th day of February', A.\nD.. 1914.\n(Seal.) P. H. NUGENT.\nClerk Circuit Court. Marion Cos., Fla.\n2-20\nIt is some satisfaction for this pa\nper to know that the council voted t#\na man for the purchase of the Dis\nmukes lot for a civic center. If the\ntrade is consummated \u2014and there are\nno impediments in the way that ws\nknow of \u2014it will be the best day\u2019s\nwork our city officials have ever done.\nIf the buildings are erected that are\ncontemplated it will become the city\u2019s\npride, and would be the pride of any\ncity. \u201cWhere there\u2019s a will, there\u2019s a\nway,\u201d and the city can find a way for\nthe erection of a fine city hall. A\nway has already been found for the\nerection of the library building.\nEvery newspaper is now speaking\nof the rapid return of prosperity. It\nis in the very air.\nDEATH OF AN AGED CITIZEN\nOklawaha, Fla., Feb. 19, 1914.\nSpecial Cor. Ocala Banner:\nMr. John Dickson, aged 84 years,\ndied at the home of his son-in-law, Mr.\nL. R. Nixon, at Homestead, Feb. 13th.\nMr. Dickson was an Englishman, and\ncame to the United States in 1850 and\nsettled in Missouri. In 1870 he moved\nto Florida, near Fantville, in this\ncounty. Twenty years ago he sold his\nhome there and bought a nice home\non I.ake Weir, where he lived until a\nyear ago. Being aged and alone, he\nwent to spend the remainder of his\nlife with his son-in-law, Mr. L. R. Nix\non, at Homestead.\nThe body arrived here on the A. C.\nL. train Sunday afternoon, where it\nwas met by a large number of the\nfriends of the deceased. The body\nwas carried to the Oklawaha ceme\ntery and laid beside his wife,, who\npreceded him a few years ago. Ser\nvices were conducted at the grave by\nRev. Evans of Belleview.\nMr. Dickson leaves to mourn his\ndeath one daughter, Mrs. I. T. Nixon,\nof this place, and two sons, living at\nPort fnglis, who have the sympathy\nof their many friends.\nA FRIEND.\nZUBER GOSSIP\nAll are sorry to hear that Mr.\nYounge had his hand badly mashed\nyesterday, but wish him speedy re\ncovery.\nMr. Perdon, of the Ocala Grocery\nCompany, and Mr. Ross of the Cheek-\nNeal Coffee Company, were in Zuber\ntoday, looking for business.\nAll are glad to know that Ralph\nShaw is able to go to school again.\nMrs. Spencer and Mrs. Shaw have\ngone to Kendrick this afternoon to\nthe W. C. T. U. meeting.\nMr. and Mrs. Baxter and H. M. Bax\nter drove into Ocala last night to see\nthe sights, and Mr. Baxter to attend\nthe K. of P. lodge.\nMr. Richie, of the Lohr Son\u2019s\nCompany, Savannah, and J. E. John\nson, of the Van DeMan-Lewis Com\npany of Jacksonville, were in Zuber\ntoday in the interest of their firms.\nMr. Barse, of the National Biscuit\nCompany, made his usual call.\nMr. Brooks is making preparations\nfor a big hunt tomorrow out towards\nFellowship.\nMr. F. M. Townsend was in Zuber\ntoday with the finest cabbage that\nhave been here this season. He had\nno touble to dispose of them, for the\nfirst store he reached bought all of\nthem.\nThe farmers are all busy as can be\ngetting ready to plant their beans,\ncantaloupes and melons. Some few\nalready have them coming up.\nAll are glad to hear that Mother\nWebb and Mrs. Guthrie of Kendrick\nare better.\nMr. Huff is visiting at Mr. Tiller\u2019s\nfor a day or so.\nMr. Gallagher of the S. Epstein\nBros. Company, Savannah, paid the\nmerchants of Zuber a visit this week.\nDr. and Mrs. Dozier of Ocala spent\nlast Saturday with Mr. and Mrs. Da\nvis.\nMr. W. H. Dawson, a lumber dealer\nfrom Jacksonville, spent Tuesday aft\nernoon with Mr. Davis.\nThe air pressure riveting machine\nthat is being used by the Sumner\nLumber Company on one of their\nlarge boilers, gives Zuber the hustling\nsound of a big city.\nMr. Z. C. Chambliss\u2019 many friends\nare delighted to see him out again,\nafter a week's illness.\nDh. w. k. lane\nSpecialist: Eye. Ear, Nose and\nThroat. Law Library building,\nGcala. Fkrida.\nNOTICE\nNotice of Election in Citra Special\nTax School District No. Ten, of Ma\nrion County, Florida, to determine\nwhether or not bonds shall be is\nsued by said district pursuant to\nthe provisions of Article 12 of the\nConstitution of the State of Florida\nand the amendment thereof adopt\ned at the general election in the\nyear 1912, and the Act of the Legis\nlature of the State of Florida, ap\nproved May 16th. 1913.\nNotice is hereby given that on the\n17th Day of March, 1914\nat Wartmana\u2019s brick building in Citra\nSpecial Tax School District No. Ten,\nin Marion county, Florida, there will\nbe held an election tb determine\nwhether or not bonds in the amount\nof eight thousand $8000) dollars\nbearing interest at the rate of 5 per\ncent., payable semi-annually, and ma\nturing 20 years from date of their is\nsuance. shall be issued by the said dis\ntrict, the proceeds of which shall be\nused for the purpose of building, en\nlarging and repairing school houses\nin the said district, and furnishing of\nthe same, and for the payment of all\nindebtedness of said district existing\nat the time of the issuance of said\nbonds, and incurred for the exclusive\nuse of the public free schools in said\ndistrict, all such buildings, improve\nments and expenditures to be for the\nexclusive use of the public free\nschools of said district.\nDone by order of the Board of Pub\nlic Instruction for the county of Ma\nrion, State of Florida, at its regular\nmeeting on the third day of Febru\nary, A. D.. 1914.\nJ. H. BRINSON, Secretary.\n1-20-41.\nTRICE\u2019S TRUMPETEER j\nI (Articles Published under this Heading fur-j\nnished by M. P. A. Bureau. Jacksonville\nThis department will be a regular\nfeature of this paper as long as the\nwriter and the publisher can agree\n[upon a satisfactory exchange for its\npublication. It carries what, to some,\nmay seem a pretentious heading, but\nit is not for show\u2014in the ordinary ac\nceptation of that. word. Its purpose\nis two-fold: First, to show you the\neditor did not write what follows;\nand, second, to proclaim what its\nname signifies, that it is a trumpeter\nupon the battlefield of life, calling to\nthe sleeping armies of liberal thought\nto awake. Too long laready have the\nsoldiers of freedom slept, and while\nthus engaged shackles more galling\nthan those of the Crusades have been\nwelded upon their mentality.\nBefore the first line is written for\npublication the \u201cdogs of war\" are\n\u201chot foot\u2019\u2019 upon my trail. But that\nonly assures me that in the past I\nhave said things which disturbed\ntheir narrow souls, and they are look\ning for something ic the future. I\ncome, however, extending not a\nbranch, hut a whole olive tree. Peace\nwould have, aud serenity, while the\nbattlements of tyranny and usurpa\ntion are stormed with the shrapnel of\nreason.\nThose who look here for coarse or\nribald entertainment will be disap\npointed. That will be left to those\nwho have no argument to make, but\nclaim a divine right to pull a mote\nfrom my eye while they refuse to ac\nknowledge the beam in their own.\n\nNo Limit to Prohibition\nThe New York World sees no lim\nit to the prevalent craze for prohibi\ntion. It says editorially: \u201cYesterday\n2000 representatives of the Anti-Sa\nloon League and the Woman\u2019s Chris\ntian Temperance Union marched to\nthe capitol in Washington to demand\nnational prohibition by an amendment\nto the constitution of the United\nStates.\n\u201cTomorrow it is likely to be the\nAnti-Cigarette League that is clamor\ning for a constitutional amendment to\nprohibit cigarette smoking, or the An\nti-Profanity League that insists on a\nconstitutional amendment to prevent\nswearing, or a Eugenics Society that\nadvocates a constitutional amendment\nto stop the birth of imperfect babies.\n\u201cEvenautlly there will be no need\nof laws or courts or churches or\nschools or preachers or charities or\nprisons. Everybody will have been\nmade wise and good and pure and in\ndustrious and healthy and prosperous\nby amendments to the constitution.\"\n\nProhibition Not Christianity\nThe New Orleans States is respon\nsible for the statement that a Louis\niana preacher cannot find any Chris\ntianity in prohibition. It quotes the\npreacher as saying:\n\u201cI want to say once for all that pro\nhibition is unreasonable and un-Chris\ntian. The moderate use of wine and\nliquor is no sin. They are the gifts\nof God, and like all other good things,\nmay be and are abused. We cannot\ncondemn them because of that fact.\n\u201cMen abuse their intelligence, their\nwealth, their talents. Let the ability\nand intelligence of those who are now\nworking to abolish the liquor traffic\nbe directed towards the annihilation\nof divorce, the greatest American\nperil, and we will be with them. Let\nthem try to pass a national amend\nment making remarriage impossible.\nProhibition has been tried time and\nagain, and failed to keep men sober.\nTo try, by civil law, to force a man\nto abstain from liquor is an infringe\nment on his personal liberty, and it\nwill always faii.\u201d \u2014ad.\nFORMER MARION COUNTY MAN\nWEDS IN JACKSONVILLE\n\nMr. B. B. Barco, formerly a well\nknown Marion county citizen, but\nwho for the past few years has resid\ned in Tampa, was quietly married in\nJacksonville at noon Wednesday to\nMrs. Ella La Fontissee-Hamilton of\nGainesville. The ceremony took place\nquietly at the Catholic parochial resi\ndence, and was witnessed by only a\nfew relatives and friends, among the\nnumber being Mrs. J. W. McCollum of\nGainesville, a sister of the bride.\nMr. and Mrs. Barco left after their\nmarriage for a bridal trip down the\neast coast, after which they will re\nside a* Clearwater, where Mr. Barco\nis now in the orange grove and real\nestate business.\nMrs. Barco has been in Ocala sever\nal times as the guest of hepr sister,\nMrs. L. J. Knight, formerly of this\ncity, and Mrs. Barco is well known to\nmany In Ocala and Marion county.\nWe extend to him and his bride our\nvery heartiest good wishes.\nRumors are in the air that Hon.\nJohn D. Robertson may become a\ncandidate for legislative honors.\nMrs. Eld ward Drake was slightly\nimproved yesterday.\nIDEAL FERTILIZERS\nBEST:\nBecause of right sources, right proportions, and\nright combinations.\no\nCHEAPEST:\nBecause of our large tonnage there is economy in\nbuying, manufacturing, and selling, and our customers\nget the benefit.\nWILSON TOOMER FERTILIZER COMPANY\nJACKSONVILLE, FLORIDA\n25 \u2014VOTES \u201428\nFor\nAddress\nIn The OCALA BANNER S\nVoting Contest.\nNOT GOOD AFTER FEBRUARY 21ST.\n\u201can honest man may have a bad title through no fault o# Hla owif\n\u201ca good man does not always mean a good title\u201d\n\u201cmen pass away, titles run on forever\u201d\n\u201can abstract of title is the only means by which y*u can determine\nwhether you are buying land or a lawsuit\u201d\nflorida title and abstract eo.\nNOMINATION BLANK\nGood For 5000 Votes\nI Nominate _\nAddress\nII IHE BAHBER iIITO CONTEST\nOnly the first nomination blank received\nfor each condidate will be counted for 5000\nvotes. Parties making nominations will not\nbelmade public under any circumstances.\nt THEJiMANAGEMENT OF\n1 THE DR. McCLANE\nt MEDICAL, SURGICAL, HYDROPATHIC AND\nELECTRIC INSTITUTE\nAnnounces the moving of the Institute Offices and\nj Treatment Rooms to the Ze Butte Building on Main\nStreet, Southeast Corner of Public Square; Entrance\nBetween The Murray Cos. and the Troxler Fruit Store.\nt Larger Charters, Flan Fully Equipped, will be Ruu n Strictly Etkkal Lues\nJ 9 A. M. to 4:30 P. M. Telephone 333\nMR. OSBORNE BUYS OUT MR.\nMUNCASTER\nSome days ago we caught a rumor\nfloating in the air that Mr. E. M. Os\nborne had bought out the fire insur\nance agency of Mr. R. C. Muncaster,\nbat both gentlemen denied the soft\nimpeachment. But it seems that the\nrumor brought the two gentlemen to\ngether, and the rumor, though an idle\none, is so no longer. The rumor was\ndiscussed, it soon began to assume a\nkind of rosy-colored shape, and event\nuated into a bona fide sale.\nThis sale puts Mr. Osborne in pos\nsession of twelve insurance compan\nies, including the qfc he originally\npossessed, and he expects to posb\nthis business for all that is in it\nMr. Osborne has bem n ctiiien of\nOcala for five years, and is n nose\nexcellent gentleman, and, though Qui\net and reserved, has made a great\nmany friends.\nWe are pleased to state that Mr.\nMuncaster has no idea of givtog up\nbis citizenship in Ocala, though last\nwhat other line at business be will\ntake on we have not been informed.\nMr. Chalmers Raysor is in from the\nfarm spending a few days. He Is look\ning better that for many years past.","height":"25455","width":"17541"}}
